defaultWLA observations specifically related to defaultcross borough procurement projectsdefault&#xa0;defaultSome pdefaultoints worthy of defaultfurtherdefault defaultexplordefaultationdefault;
default              
defaultMost boroughs are very supportive of collaboration at the top level of the political and administrative 
defaultstrata.  It makes sense after all to seek economies of scale and to reduce management overheads for both the contracting entities as well as the client organisations.
default&#xa0;
defaultPolitical realities however have to be recognised and taken into consideration.
defaultBoroughs
default will have their own individual Missions Statements, Visions and Policy Directives.  These will have been develop
defaulted
default from manifestos and electoral promises with a view to delivering to resident
defaults
default outcomes that are politically desirable and that politicians 
defaultare
default held accountable for.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen viewed across a multi borough environment, aligning procurement activity that dovetails these absolutes into collective deliverables is 
defaultchallenging
default.  There will always be borough specific imperatives from a local perspective
default that need to be understood.
default 
defaultThat said, the common theme across all public sector bodies is the obligation to 
defaultoperate
default as efficient
defaultly
default as possible, to seek and to gain best value, and to drive out excess costs.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is 
defaultarguably the job of procurement 
defaultprofessi
defaultonals
default and their client organisations to make the economic case for collaboration. To do this they have to understand how such a case may be constructed and where derived benefits will flow from.  
defaultT
defaulthis goes beyond simply specifying a requirement and multipl
defaultying this up across a number of boroughs. It is more about understanding from a bidding 
defaultcontractor’s
default perspective how they can
default be incentivised to
default reshape the way services are configured and delivered so that costs can be driven out and benefits delivered in
default parallel with enhancing the quality of the outcomes. These skills are and this knowledge is not always readily available in-house to boroughs. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is often at this client / procurement level that collaborations become frustrated as there can be a disconn
defaultect between the high level political will and the ability of the departmental teams to
default; 
defaulta) 
defaultbe able
default to 
defaultsee
default the benefits of such and 
defaultmake change 
defaulthappen, 
defaultb) be able to and objectively assess and 
defaultarticulate 
defaultupwards 
defaultthe benefits 
defaultand 
defaultrisks involved with making s
defaultuch changes
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs mentioned previously collaboration can be frustrated where it is not high enough on 
defaultthe
default agenda to bring it to the forefront of peoples thinking and more importantly their future planning.
default 
defaultMore often than not 
defaultborough 
defaultprocurers
default are content with satisfying the
defaultir
default immediate requirements, rather than planning for the future. They will often cite lack of resources, time or other priorities as matters that divert them from pursuing collaboration.
default&#xa0;
defaultAn underlying issue may be that collaboration threatens the status quo within an individual borough and individuals or the departments they work in may see it as portending the future and their control over it.   As with all change unless people can see th
defaulteir role in the future they may well challenge it or seek to frustrate it.
default&#xa0;
defaultOther matters that can frustrate collaboration or procurement improvement can be;
default&#xa0;
default•
default              
defaultLack of visiondefault /default defaultApathy / Parochialismdefault / Lack of confidencedefault•default              defaultOrganisational inadequacydefault / inadequate skill base to take on new challengesdefault•default              defaultLimited capacity or confidence in dealing with defaulta changed risk/ reward profiledefault•default              defaultMistrust of partners in other boroughsdefault / Political alignmentdefault•default              defaultFear of lack of controldefault / individual budgetingdefault / Poor undersdefaulttanding of riskdefault•default              defaultHigh staff defaultturnover /default churn / overabundance of interim staff default&#xa0;
defaultThese matters can be overcome through dialogue and working with colleagues to share a clear vision of the future from senior levels downwards, however this takes time and care
default. Peoples concerns need to be aired and valued and they need to know that they will be supported in any new initiative. 
default&#xa0;
defaultStaff will need to recognise that the general direction of travel within the procurement fraternity is towards collaboration and that 
defaultthey will be given support to up skill and embrace this on behalf, not only of their own employers, but also the wider regional public sector community.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs previously discussed, many 
defaultlocal authority procurement staff were traditionally recruited on the basis that they were required to understand the corporate and European procurement rules and are able to ensure control over and compliance with these strictly controlled requirements.
default 
defaultT
defaulthis offers up a level of protection for Authorities from challenges from aggrieved bidders and also from the EU commission itself from charges of non-compliance. Both of which can incur costly remedies if 
defaulta borough is 
defaultfound to be at fault.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis being the
default case then the room for a
default more
default entrepreneurial approach to procurement is not only limited but could be viewed as being positively discouraged by more risk adverse boroughs.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs a norm then it could be suggested that the staff that populate procurement dep
defaultartments may not have the
default incentive
default,
default 
defaultaptitude or the proficiency to engage fully in what the private sector may classify as normal commercially lead behaviour
default. 
defaultN
defaultegotiation and deal making 
defaultmay therefore 
defaultnot be familiar territory for them.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is relatively easy to hide behind process and restrictive rules to avoid being commercial driven, however without challenging the status quo and testing the art of the possible the ability to drive through change and make value driven deals will be frus
defaulttrated. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTraining can be given to enhance commercial skills however instilling the confidence into individuals to plan for and to use these skill in a live procurement environment may be more of a problem if those staff are not naturally inclined to engag
defaulte in this activity or do not believe they were recruited to do so.
